The paper deals with fundamental problems in distributed networks, such as building spanning trees and minimum spanning trees, which are typically studied in the Distributed Computing (cs.DC) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. The paper also discusses communication costs and message complexity, which are relevant to the Networked and Internet Systems (cs.NI) sub-category. The use of Monte Carlo algorithms and high probability success rates suggest a possible connection to the Algorithms (cs.AL) sub-category. Finally, the mention of constructing low diameter trees may indicate a connection to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
